XPO Terminal XHG reported a spill of an unknown amount an unidentified product coming off of a trailer that pulled into their yard that had impacted the trailer itself as well as the asphalt beneath it. ERTS dispatched First Call Environmental to conduct cleanup. At 0330 ET, FCE personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 40-gallons of UN170 "Descaler" released from a 55 gallon poly drum. The drum was crushed resulting in a release to a 4' x 4' area of the trailer floor and an 8' x 10' area of asphalt lot below the trailer. The damaged drum was containerized into a 95-gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas. Sodium bicarb was then used to neutralize the impacted areas. All waste was placed into two 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On November 8, 2022, at 0236 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal LSL experienced an approximate 2-gallon release of UN1760 “Sikafloor-293 Part B” from a 5-gallon metal pail. The release impacted the trailer floor due to a pallet nail puncture. No soils, drains, or waterways were reported to have been impacted. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental to conduct all on site cleanup operations. On November 8, 2022, at 0635 EST, E3 personnel arrived on site and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to a 15' x 15' area of the trailer floor due to a pallet nail puncture. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area and then collected along with the damaged pail into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Aircraft N403YK was loaded for a flight to PADG. The flight departed normally from PANC. On climb out the crew noticed a fume smell coming from the cargo compartment. They verified the dangerous goods with the flight support (load master) and decided to return to PANC to address the issue. The crew did declare an emergency and landed uneventfully. The cargo team cleaned up the small amount of spilled diesel fuel and drained more out of the generator. After discussing with the flight crew the cargo was reloaded and the flight was completed.

GE personnel installed a cap on the tote, then wiped down the cargo and containerized all UN3082-impacted product in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal in the facility waste stream. The remediated tote was sent for normal transport.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XSW notified ERTS of strong fumes coming from a trailer, with a shipment of UN2363 Ethyl Mercaptan Class 3 PG I on the trailer. ERTS dispatched contractors to assess the trailer. Contractors arrived onsite and allowed the trailer to air out, then made entry into the trailer. They used a 5 gas meter and reported no readings for LEL. O2 was in a good level as well. Crew found 3 large tanks containing UN2363 Ethyl Mercaptan but had no signs of a leak. The cylinders were separated in the parking lot outside. Contractors conducted a soap test, but it did not produce any results of leaks. A 5 gas was placed close to the valve of one of the tanks and a 1.3ppm reading of H2S was recorded. Crew recommend that the trailer be left open over night to air out and that the tanks be left outside to off gas. A final reading on the tanks was taken and the H2S was down to 0.6ppm. The tanks were coned off and terminal personnel directed to stay clear of the area. No waste was generated. Tanks left onsite for consignee pick-up.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

SequenceEvent: On 11/07/2022 between 6:20pm and 6:30pm, Outbound sort manager called QA over radio to notify us that there was a leaking Hazmat package in delivery vehicle in work area 1016. QA removed damaged package from delivery vehicle, placed in proper Hazmat bin and staged in hazmat cage for future processing. After package was staged in Hazmat Cage, QA notified Pickup and delivery management of the situation via Email. Package was inspected by QA on 11/08/2022 to determine damage.  It was discovered that one metal can of Certified Mile-Hi with Octane Boost Gasoline improver was dented and leaking contents. Only one can was damaged out of the six total in the package.  Upon inspection of the packaging it was discovered that contents were not shipped in regulated fiberboard box.  Damaged package Report was completed on 11/08/2022 and QA is currently awaiting further instructions on how to proceed. DescribePack: Top and side of body of can dented. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Upon notification of leakage, package was retrieved and staged in Fedex Ground regulated bin for leaking Hazmat. Due to size of packaging, QA had to open package and remove all six cans and place them in bin. Packaging was kept together with cans. Leaking fluid cleaned with absorbent pads. Contents then placed in hazmat cage under ventilation. P&D management then notified via Email of situation.

column168: SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON OUR UNLOADING DOCK LEAKING INSIDE THE TRAILER. THE MANAGER CALLED OUT FOR QA AND ONE OF OUR ADMINS WENT TO RETRIEVE THE PACKAGE. THEY PLACED THE HAZMAT IN A LINED TOTE AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO THE HAZ CAGE FOR INSPECTION. DescribePack: OUT OF THE FOUR BOTTLES OF DIVERSEY SUMA GRILL AND OVEN CLEANER 1 GALLON THREE HAD LOOSE CAPS CAUSING THEM TO SPILL OUT INTO THE PACKAGE. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: EVERYTHING WAS PLACED IN A LINED DRUM FOR PROCESSING.

SequenceEvent: DRUM WAS DISCOVERED BY A HANDLER LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM SO IT WAS PLACED ON A TOTE AND SENT TO THE HAZMAT CAGE DescribePack: BOTTOM OF THE DRUM HAS A SMALL CRACK DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PLACED ON A TOTE TO STOP FURTHER LEAKAGE IN THE WORK AREA

SequenceEvent: The Package was found in front of QA Hazmat Cage inside a red Hazmat bin, laying on its side, leaking liquid out onto the box. I then opened it to investigate the package then proceeded to do a DPR on the Hazmat. DescribePack: the pail inside was leaking from the closures and leaking out onto the box DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: package was placed inside a red hazmat bin

column168: SequenceEvent: Package was discovered to be leaking in the unload. QA was called and package was segregated to prevent further damage to other packages. I am unsure of how the package was made to be leaking as I was unable to recreate the leak or see any obvious signs of damage. DescribePack: Unknown, unable to recreate spill. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was segregated into a tote a brought to QA for processing.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package was discovered leaking on the van lines, once discovered it was segregated and brought to QA for inspection. Upon inspection it was discovered that the cap had come loose which caused the leak. DescribePack: Loose cap. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was segregated into a damage tote to prevent damage to other packages and brought to QA for processing.

1.  X-2022110843 SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND AT THE 500 BELT AND IT APPEARED TO BE WET. UPON INSPECTION I FOUND THAT ONE OF THE 4 L JUGS HAD A LOOSE CAP AND SOME SPILLED OUT INTERNALLY. column168: SequenceEvent: Package found during unload with small amount of powder at base of box. Box inspected by QA and determined damage item. DescribePack: Plastic bag of heavy-duty detergent with bleach found with small tear inside causing powder to spill out. No additional inner packing inside box (ex. paper). No visible damage to outer package. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Bag placed with hole on top to negate spill.

SequenceEvent: discovered damaged on load side. package was dropped.upon inspection all four caps came loose on bottles leaking out approx 40 oz of content. DescribePack: Failure was due to package being dropped causing caps to loosen resulting in internal leakage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: fold absorb was used to address spill package was placed in hazmat tote and put under ventilation system.

SequenceEvent: Package was found leaking in trailer and was removed. Leak started before trailer was dispatched to station. DescribePack: 2 inch crack on bottom of pail DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: Pail was removed from trailer and put into a container to contain the spill

SequenceEvent: package arrived on the trailer saturated and deteriorating, leakage was discovered, box was removed from unload and placed in proper hazmat red pail DescribePack: one side of box is falling apart soaked in corrosive liquid DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: gloves were worn and box was removed from unload and placed in proper holding area. No liquid was released onto floor

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: SequenceEvent: The sequence of events that led to the incident of the damage hazmat was improper placement in trailer. However, the action taken at time of discovery, the package was then isolated away from other non-hazardous packages for the safety of other's. DescribePack: The package failure of UN1830, Sulfuric Acid, 16oz, plastic bottles, shipped in plastic bags with tie's; failed due to loose cap becoming loose on bottling in transportation. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: Isolation of the Hazmat was mitigated to maintain safety of the crew.

SequenceEvent: Found by Abraham Reyes on the unload team. He found this package wet and torn. Upon further inspection there was loose lid in package and also orientation arrows were not followed during loading process. DescribePack: One of the 1-liter bottles had a loose cap and product leaked out. DurationRel: 8 and MitigateEffect: Clean-up was done immediately.

SequenceEvent: package was found on the dock laying on side down sand was poured on spill package was place in plastic bag taken to hazmat cage. DescribePack: Package had a leak at the side seam and loose cap about one inch DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: package was upright and sand was poured on place in plastic bag and taken to cage.

SequenceEvent: Found as damaged during the unload process. DescribePack: One of the caps to the containers was cracked at the top causing spillage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Put in lined tote & taken to hazmat cage
SequenceEvent: Package was found as damaged during the unload process. DescribePack: Loose cap DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Put in lined tote & taken to hazmat cage

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE WAS DROPPED/FELL OFF BELT, LANDED ON THE TOP CORNER OF THE BOX CRUSHING THE TOP/CAP OF THE INNER PACKAGES CAUSING INNER LEAKAGE. PACKAGE WAS PICKED UP AND PLACED IN HAZMAT TOTE. DescribePack: TOP OF TWO BOTTLES DENTED - BROKEN CAP ONE BOTTLE UNABLE TO TIGHTEN CAUSING INNER LEAKAGE DurationRel: 7 and MitigateEffect: PACKAGE PLACED IN RED HAZMAT TOTE...LATER BOTTLES WERE TURNED TO UPRIGHT POSITION TO STOP LEAKAGE.

SequenceEvent: THE HAZMAT WAS LOCATED ON THE LOAD SIDE DURING THE DAY SORT.THE PACKAGE WAS WET AND LEAKING. THE CONTENTS WITHIN SHOWED  THAT ONE OF THE GLASS BOTTLES HAD BROKEN CAUSING THE INTERNAL LEAKAGE. DescribePack: contents broken DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: used absorbent material to soak up liquid

SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE WAS BEING UNLOADED AND THE PH NOTICE THAT THE BOX WAS WET AND QA WAS CALLED OVER TO RETRIEVE THE PACAKGE DescribePack: THE CAPS ON 2 OF THE BOTTLES WERE LOOSE AND THE LIQUID LEAKED INSIDE THE PACKAGE DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM

column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

SequenceEvent: Found at vsa. To open it up to find four different hazmat's in a package that isn't declared. DescribePack: The cap was loose. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Quickly put into a tote.

SequenceEvent: Package arrived wet at OKLA731. Package came from KCMO644 trailer 455426. Package was placed in a hazmat tote upon discovery. DescribePack: Package was dropped due to mishandling, causing one of the caps to bust open and contents to leak. Package was soaked and ripped open upon impact. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: The package, in a hazmat tote, is then isolated and secured in a hazmat cage.

SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE WAS BEING LOADED ONTO A TRAILER AND THE MANAGER CALLED QA SAYING THAT THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING AND QA WENT TO RETRIEVE THE PACKAGE DescribePack: THE CAPS ON THE BOTTLES WERE LOOSE AND THE LIQUID LEAKED INSIDE THE PACKAGE DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM

SequenceEvent: THE SEQUENCE OF EVENTS IS UNKNOWN. DescribePack: THIS PACKAGE CONTAINED TWO PLASTIC CONTAINERS OF WATER TREATMENT SOLUTION. UNFORTUNATELY, THIS PACKAGE BECAME DAMAGED AT SOME POINT. SequenceEvent: PKG WAS UNLOADED 11/14 AND IT WAS DISCOVERED IT HAD LEAKED INSIDE THE BOX. BOX WAS GIVEN TO QA. IT WAS THEN SECURED AND INSPECTED. Employee stated the side appeared wet on 11/12. Pkg sat at the damage area till Monday 11/14. DescribePack: 2 OF THE 4 CAPS WERE LOOSE AND LIQUID LEAKED INTO THE BOX. column168: Package was called into the spill office at our Memphis hub location when it was seen during night time sort operations  a package presented with a wet corner indicating the possibility of a leak inside.  Package was a fibreboard box marked as containing UN 1263.  Further inspection found the package contained 2 metal cans each filled 3.78L of UN 1263.  each can was individually wrapped in a moisture barrier.  Bubble wrap was used for dunnage, and it was not reported if the metal cans had positive closure.  It was reported one of the can opened during travel and allowed for inner commodity to leak out.  Package was placed in a steel salvage drum and shipper was contacted for an amended shipper's declaration for continued travel.

column168: At 1654 EST, XPO Terminal XLF notified ERTS of a spill that occurred on the dock in Woodland, PA. The spill consisted of a poly pails of UN2796 Securiganth Acid Conditioner, which arrived at the terminal in a damaged condition. The can was found leaking on a pallet likely due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product released to the dock floor in a 5' x 10' area due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected. The damaged pail and all impacted absorbents were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum which was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: 11/10/2022, at 10:48 hours, CSX personnel in the CSXT Manville yard discovered the SHPX222814, a residue tank car of UN 1993 Waste Flammable Liquid, having a vapor release from the manway area of the rail car. The rail car was isolated and GEOCYCLE was notified along with Kemtell (no report # issued). MEI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car was having a vapor release from the manway area of the rail car. Upon checking the manway gasket. The gasket was found to be improperly installed and cracked. The issue identified where corrected and were communicated to the shipper Marvin Sparks 843-826-1746 marvin.sparks@geocycle.com . Contractor personnel installed new nozzle gasket secured the rail car. The rail car was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.

column168: 1. X-2022111044 FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET AND LEAKING BY A SORTER ON BOXLINE-3. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AD NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 4 MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED AND A 2' RADIUS PUDDLE CLEANED UP, THEN ALL MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER ISNSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WAS CRACKED, CAUSING APPROX 2 QUARTS OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO, THEN OUTSIDE OF THE CARTON. THE INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF CORRUGATED PARTITIONS AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 51 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).   2. X-2022111045 FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY A SORTER ON BOXLINE-3. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. column168: Part of a 11 piece shipment, this package was called into the spill office at our Memphis hub location when it was seen the package was leaking.  Package was found during normal sort operations and is the second package of this shipment to be found leaking.  Package consisted of a fibreboard box with 5 gallon plastic bucket inside.  There was no moisture barrier nor dunnage reported.  It was seen the lid of the bucket was loose from the bucket and allowed for an estimated 6L of UN 3982 to leak out of the package.  Package was placed in a steel salvage drum and shipper was contacted for disposition.

column168: On November 29, 2022, at 0830 ET, approximately 1385 gallons of Blitz 22 was released due to a single vehicle accident that occurred when the truck struck a deer resulted in a vehicle roll over. Haz-Mat Response were dispatched by ERTS to manage and oversee environmental operations. Upon arrival Haz-Mat Response personnel observed smoke and fumes that were blowing across the interstate to the south. Haz-Mat Response personnel donned PPE and began to transfer the remaining contents from the totes into new totes that had been delivered while the fire department hose down the totes. The transferred product was placed into 2-275 gallon totes, 9-225 gallon totes, and 1-300 gallon tote. One additional tote was generated with the rinse water. The broken totes were broken down and placed into one (1) roll-off box along with the debris from the trailer. The new totes were transported to the DOT yard in Shelton, NE along with the roll-off box to be staged for disposal. The median was secured by Haz-Mat Response personnel for future remediation.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: At 1446 EST, XPO notified ERTS of rejected cargo located at XSD.  It was reported that a 375-gallon poly tote of UN2735 “3,3-Methylenebis(5-methyloxazolidine)” was rejected by the consignee due to unknown reasons. The Tote was found on OS&D and leaked approximately 1-teaspoon of the product at the spout area due to a possible damaged tote or a seal leak.  The terminal requested a contractor out to inspect the tote for damages. ERTS dispatched a contractor for assessment. Contractors arrived onsite and advised were a few drops of liquid under the spout of the tote which they pH tested at a 9. Crew advised it didn't look like there is was damage to the tote. The material was transferred into a new tote as precaution. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Improper Blocking & Bracing

On November 04, 2022, Landstar Ranger contacted ERTS to report a spill that occurred inside a trailer located at 122 Fitz Henry Rd in Smithton, PA. The spill consisted of a UN1866 resin solution, likely damaged due to improper loading as the contents were found along the walls of the trailer and the drum was dented along the side, resulting in approximately 0.5 gallons released. Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed a 1 ft-by 2ft area of wood trailer floor that was impacted by the released material. Hepaco personnel stated that the damaged container was not present. Hepaco personnel applied a degreaser to the impacted area and used absorbent pads to wipe down the residue. The spent absorbent pads were placed into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The generated waste containers were transported offsite by Hepaco personnel to process for disposal.

column168: The delivery site originally wanted us to leave with the product as they had enough in their tank.  We worked with the shipper who authorized us to do a partial delivery.  The driver was not familiar with the process of doing a partial delivery.  When the receiver told her to stop the tank was completely full instead of leaving 10% headspace like we requested.  This means she could not use her airline to blow the lines clear through what we call the bleeder valve system.  She now had to do a 'wet break' which she was unfamiliar with and did not stop and call one of our safety representatives for guidance.  She opened the bleeder valve and let product drain off until it stopped.  However she never walked the hoses to the bleeder valve to drain off additional product.  We recommend draining off 5 gallons in to buckets to ensure there is sufficient headspace in the hose when disconnecting from the highest point first.  Since this was not done when the hose was disconnected product rushed out the end of the delivery hose and overshot her spill bucket and on to the ground.  After she capped off that hose end she went to disconnect from the customer fill line and again a little product splashed out again.
column169: The customer ordered too much product.  We are working with them to discourage this process so we don't end up doing partial unloads.  Our driver was brought in for training refreshers on using her 'stop work authority' and call for assistance.   Internally when a customer says they have enough product and to not attempt delivery, we should follow that guidance vs tring to do partial deliveries.  Customer Service and Operations are now aware of the correct operating protocols.

column168: XPO Terminal USU contacted ERTS to request assistance with cleaning an approximate 20-gallon spill of UN1987 "SDA 3C 190 Proof" that was released from a 55-gallon poly drum after being punctured by a forklift. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and containment. Contractors arrived onsite and advised there were no visible signs of any released material. Anything released had evaporated. The damaged drum was containerized into an 85-gallon poly overpack. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On November 19, 2022, at 1854 ET. Circle K reported UN1203 "Gasoline" released 30-gallons from a 8700-gallons from a cargo tanker due to a single vehicle accident. The tanker arrived at the gas station and turned a tight corner into a steel pole damaging the loading hose. ERTS dispatched Allied International Emergency (Allied) to perform all onsite clean up operations. On November 19, 2022, at 2120 ET, Allied arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of gasoline released impacting a 35-feet (ft.) by 15-ft. area of concrete and a 30-gallon metal drum containing 5-gallons of gasoline. Allied utilized absorbents to clean the impacted concrete areas. Allied collected and containerized the impacted absorbents into (1) 55-gallon metal drum. Allied transported the (1) 55-gallon metal drum gasoline impacted absorbents and the 30-gallon metal drum containing the 5-gallons of gasoline off site for disposal.

column168: On November 16, 2022, at 0600 EST, an XPO Logistics tractor trailer was involved in a single vehicle rollover accident. As a result, the unit experienced a cargo release of UN1760 “Reglone Desiccant” from a 120-gallon poly tote. Approximately 30- gallons of product released to the snow and soil shoulder. No drains or waterways were reported to have been impacted. ERTS dispatched Rock Leaf Water Environmental (RLW) to perform emergency response and remediation. On November 16, 2022, at 0905 EST, RLW personnel arrived on site and confirmed approximately 30-gallons of product released to 2’ x 75’ area of soil and snow. RLW advised the containers were not damaged but released from a gasket/seal system not designed to support the container being inverted. Released material was collected by scraping the impacted snow and soil with a skid steer. All cargo was then transported to the XPO terminal located in Fridley, MN for continued shipment. The soil remaining was confirmed clean by the DOT and RLW with no further remediation needed. All contaminated soil, snow, and absorbents were placed into two 55-gallon poly drums and removed from site pending disposal. Please see attached photos (Appendix 2). On December 8, 2022, RLW returned to the spill site to complete confirmation soil sampling for TCLP Pesticides per MN Pollution Control Agency request. Due to wet conditions as a result of recent snow melt, site restoration will take place at a later date.

column168: Package was offered to the spill office at our Memphis Hub facility.  Package was found during normal sort operations in a baggage cart with leakage coming from the bottom of the box. Package was placed in a steel salvage drum and shipper was contacted for an amended shippers declaration for continued travel.

column168: On 11/10/22 at approximately 8:42 pm, a fully loaded LIN tanker was involved in a non-preventable vehicle accident which resulted in a rollover. While approaching an intersection on a 2-lane road, the Air Products driver remained in the right lane, with the intention of proceeding straight through the intersection. As the Air Products driver entered the intersection, a passenger sedan from the opposite lane of travel turned in front of the Air Products tractor, resulting in a collision. The force of the collision resulted in loss of control and a rollover. The trailer vessel cracked causing full release of product onto the roadway. Upon investigation the inner-outer vessel cracked at the front of the trailer from impact with roadway. Trailer lost vacuum and emptied 5673 liquid gallons of LIN within 2 hours. Photos of accident scene attached.  The NRC initial report did state that at least one person was taken to hospital for treatment, however this was a result of the accident and not the hazmat release.
column169: Investigation is ongoing, current insurance hold on the tractor/trailer. Once released, the full investigation of product loss will continue.  A full inspection of the inner vessel will be performed. Maintenance records and rehab records will also be reviewed.

column168: Our driver pulled up to the plant and the gate was locked. He called dispatch and an operator from the plant called him with the code to the gate. Driver pulled in and got hooked up and he spoke with the operator again and asked about the level in the tank. The clock gauge is not accurate and the audible overfill alarm had been removed. They had an electronic reading in the office but no one was on site. The operator told our driver over the phone that the tank reading was at 45% and it would fit. Due to a hurricane, The site had ordered too much fuel because they had pulled their trucks off the road and did not use what they normally do. The operator did not take this into account when he told our driver it would fit. Shield Engineering managed the cleanup. Product was contained to AST pad.
column169: Customer will reimburse Eagle for cleanup.

column168: HGTU 241486 was found to have a small leak from the bottom outlet valve during yard inspection at the CP Bensenville Intermodal Yard on 11-14-22.   A qualified ER Contractor was dispatched to the site, and air monitoring equipment was used to establish that no elevated levels of pyridine were found in the area.  The Contractor subsequently found that the bottom discharge valve cap was loose and the internal valve gasket surrounding the front flange was peeling, allowing for product to slowly drip out of the flange.   Gore PTFE gasket tape was used to make new gaskets, and the leak was stopped.  Spilled material was cleaned up, and placed into a drum for disposal.
column169: Continued emphasis with Offerors/Shippers to conduct thorough inspections prior to movement will reduce valve failures in the field.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While loading freight, drum was punctured by a forklift, which resulted in the loss of approximately 50 gallons of free product to the asphalt/concrete surface at loading area. Alliance Ground International applied absorbent material to contain the free product to immediate area, Miller Environmental Group was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, Miller Environmental offloaded the skid and found the damaged drum. Damaged drum was overpacked and additional absorbent material was applied to the impacted impervious surface. Miller Environmental proceeded to recover the impacted absorbents, break down contaminated skid, and containerized all spent absorbents and cleanup debris into 5 55-gallon drums. Disposal will be coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There was no impact to surface soils or threat to enter state waters. Free product was contained to an impervious surface and recovered without further incident. There were no injuries or exposures.
column169: Alliance Ground International will continue to train and reiforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all  personnel

column168: On November 21, 2022, Landstar Inway reported a release of UN2796, Sulfuric Acid that resulted in the asphalt parking lot and a soil lot being impacted. Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel stated that a company by the name of MEI was on scene cleaning the release that had been dispatched by the county. The Hepaco supervisor remained onsite to supervise the cleanup; however Hepaco crew stood down. MEI personnel located and determined that three (3) totes had been damaged due to improper preparation for transit that resulted in the cargo to shift/rolled over. MEI personnel stated that 650 gallons of material had been released that mostly impacted the asphalt parking lot in a 60 yard by 20 yard area. MEI deployed Soda Ash and dirt to contain the released material. The remaining material in the damaged totes was transferred to two (2) new totes. MEI personnel pressure washed the bottom of the trailer and then reloaded the cargo. After the trailer was moved, the contractor used a street sweeper to recover the soil, soda ash and impacted wash water on the parking lot and place into one (1) roll-off box and transported offsite for disposal.  On November 22, 2022, a second clean-up was requested by Landstar Inway. Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel used a pressure washer to clean the totes and the trailer of debris/residue.  Two (2) 55-gallon poly drums of absorbents used to recover the wash water were generated and transported offsite for disposal.

column168: The customer's checked bag had flown from Los Cabos to Phoenix an American Airlines Flight 2841/20Nov had cleared CBP and TSA in Phoenix and was brought to the baggage transfer point to connect to American Airlines Flight 623 to Kansas City. The bag caught fire at the baggage transfer point. The bag was pulled to the ground and the fire went out on its own. The cause of the fire was a torch lighter in the customer's bag. The weight of the bag must have pOshed on the activation valve of the lighter and it self ignited inside the customefs bag. Airport Crash, Fire, Rescue and Airport Police responded and spoke to the customer along with American Airlines who informed the customer that torch Iighters are never permitted on American Airlines aircraft. The bag was sent to the American Airlines Baggage Service Office where it and the lighter are being held for FAA investigation.

SequenceEvent: PLASTIC JERRICAN WAS FOUND AT APPROX. 5 AM UPRIGHT ON THE GROUND, SET ASIDE BY THE PACKAGE HANDLERS WORKING THE TUGGER STATION. THE CAN WAS THEN WIPED WITH ABSORBENT PADS, AS WELL AS THE 1TSP OF LIQUID ON THE FLOOR FOUND NEARBY THE CAN. AFTER WIPING, MORE LIQUID WAS FOUND SEEPING THROUGH THE TAPE, INDICATING THE FAILURE WAS WITH THE HAZMAT. DescribePack: SEALS WERE NOT PROPERLY FITTED OR TAPED OVER. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PACKAGE WAS PROMPTLY SET ON A CART AND IN A QA AREA. MORE ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED ON THE FLOOR WHERE THE CAN HAD PREVIOUSLY SAT.

Additional corrective actions are being developed and will be implemented in the coming days/weeks.   Preliminary Actions to Prevent Recurrence:   ATL Domestic Line has implemented a verification process requiring all assets shipped COMAT be verified by serial number and signed off by the employee; that sign off is then validated by management. Delta Logistics has initiated a system-wide inventory of all parts to validate part numbers and accuracy within the system to ensure the number on the part and in the system match.

column168: On 11/25/2022 at approximately 1500 PST, our driver was heading eastbound along Grizzly Flats Rd. This road contains many narrow curves. While navigating the route the driver reported an encounter with another vehicle "hugging the centerline" and moved as far over as possible to allow the oncoming vehicle to pass. Upon execution of this decision the driver! truck left the asphalt surfaced - hard pack of the roadway. Directly adjacent to the white fog line at the location of the accident was a substantial shoulder drop off of approximately 18 inches. Consequently, the driver attempted to correct the situation to quickly bring the truck back to the asphalt surface. The resulting improper procedure of over-steering caused the truck to rollover sideways onto the roadway resulting in contact with another vehicle traveling on the same road. Upon impact with the other vehicle our truck continued to move and came to rest on its side off the roadway. The accident resulted in the occupants of the other vehicle going to hospital to be checked out and later released. Our driver signed a letter of declination at the scene to be treated for injuries, but at the managers request visited the ER to be checked out for possible injuries and required post-accident drug! alcohol screening. The rollover caused a small crack in the piping of the CTMV and damage (denting) to the tank. The damage to the piping allowed the release of approximately 200 gallons of product in vapor form from the vessel. In order to correct the issue, product had to be removed from the tank in order to upright the vehicle. Our responding personnel were able to remove enough product by means of controlled flaring to allow the vehicle to be up righted, the leak was stopped allowing the safe removal of the vehicle and remaining product from the scene. Upon completed transfer of the CTMV back to the home facility the remaining product was removed from the vessel.
column169: Currently, drivers are required to complete industry specific training, Hazmat training, rollover prevention training, road test upon hire before assignment of job duties to include operation of a CTMV. We are modifying our requirements to include two ride along evaluations being performed by the General Manager annually and requiring Rollover Prevention training annually in addition to the initial training.

column168: On Nov 11, 2022 approximately around 7:45 PM Republic driver Art Thatcher pulled over at a Flying J's truck stop for his l0hr rest period while in transit to Kimera Chemical in Mobile AL. Around 8pm while Art was conducting his Post trip, he identified a strong smell while walking around the truck. Art noticed a few drops of liquid substance coming from under the trailer close to the king pin. Art immediately grabbed is spill kit and applied it to the area where the liquid was coming from. Art called the on call supervisor around 8:05pm to report to the management team on a possible leak containing Acetic Acid. Art was instructed to call Chemtrec at 8:15pm for further instructions. Chemtrec referred Republic Services to call Environmental Management to assist with the containment and transferring the tanker to another if needed. A replacement tanker was dispatched the following morning while Mr. Thatcher stayed with the contained tanker. Between the time when Mr. Thatcher identified the dripping tanker at 7:45 PM and the completion of the product transfer by Environmental Management less than 1 gallon were contained by the spill kit. Approximately 3:10 PM the next day, the Environmental management Team arrived on site to contain spill. The off load started at 520 PM and was completed at 7:00 PM. Per Environmental Management, there was no product that spilled on the ground
column169: This Trailer has been professionally cleaned and is in the process of being inspected, so that a root cause of the drip can be identified and corrected.

Carton had no Hazmat markings, labels or directional arrows. Only label was original FedEx shipping label. DescribePack: Leaking can was dented and bent at the base of the cap/spout. column168: On November 16, 2021 at approximately 14:45 PM, a High Energy(H/E)(potential thermal runaway) condition occurred on flight 1574 outbound from Kingston, Jan=^aica(KIN), inbound to Miami, Florida(MIA). The event took place during cruising altitude and during main cabin service. The event was approximately an hour prior to landing, putting the event at approximately 14:45 pm to 15:00 pm. I, Flight Attendant#1 received a call from the back galley by FA#2. She notified me of a passenger who had a vaping device near the back of the plane, who complained to her that the device was becoming extremely hot in their pocket. The passenger was identified as a Mr. Kenneth Steven Snell, seat number 29E. FA asked if we should use the fire containment bag, and I agreed that would be best to contain the H/E condition being omitted by the vape device. In this report there was a question for what occurred (Fire, Fumes/Odor, or smoke), there was no option for H/E conditions so I selected smoke, however, no smoke came from the device. The event was only a High Energy condition A event(overheating but no smoke or fire). The fire containment bag was delivered to the FAs in the back galley to treat and contain the over heating vape device. The bag was then stored in an empty cart in the back galley and monitored by FA 2,3 and 4. The Captain was notified immediately after the fire containment bag was donned. No escalating conditions occurred during flight. Upon arrival at Miami international airport, the gate agent's were immediately notified and a flight service manager came onboard to get a report of the event. Upon all passengers deplaning, the fire containment bag was removed by the flight services manager for record and documentation. Request for new equipment was placed for the aircraft as well. The vaping product was an"MBox vape" by Athena Vapors. Item was cool to the touch after being treated and contained. No other incidents and no injuries occurred in this event. END OF REPORT.
